╚═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

NEXUS: "The station's DNS server is the brain of our name resolution system.
       When you type 'server' instead of '172.20.0.20', DNS translates that
       name into an address. Understanding this system is critical - many
       network failures are actually DNS failures in disguise."

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

OBJECTIVE
═════════
DNS (Domain Name System) is the phone book of the network. When an application
needs to connect to "server", it first asks DNS for the IP address.

Our station has a custom DNS server (dnsmasq) that knows all our containers.
Learn to query DNS directly to understand and troubleshoot name resolution.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

TASKS
═════

[ ] Task 1: Basic DNS Lookup
    Command: dig server
    Examine the output: QUESTION section, ANSWER section, and SERVER line.

[ ] Task 2: Short Format Lookup
    Command: dig +short server
    Get just the IP address without verbose output.

[ ] Task 3: Query Different Record Types
    Command: dig server A
    Command: dig server AAAA
    A records are IPv4, AAAA records are IPv6.

[ ] Task 4: Reverse DNS Lookup
    Command: dig -x 172.20.0.20
    Look up a hostname from an IP address.

[ ] Task 5: Query a Specific DNS Server
    Command: dig @172.20.0.53 server
    Command: dig @8.8.8.8 server
    See why external DNS cannot resolve our internal names.

[ ] Task 6: Test External Resolution
    Command: dig +short google.com
    Our DNS forwards unknown queries to the internet.

[ ] Task 7: Alternative DNS Tools
    Command: nslookup server
    Command: host server
    Try other DNS utilities available on the system.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

KEY CONCEPTS
════════════
  dig             - DNS lookup utility (most detailed)
  dig +short      - Just the answer, no extra info
  dig @server     - Query a specific DNS server
  dig -x IP       - Reverse lookup (IP to name)
  nslookup/host   - Simpler DNS lookup tools

RECORD TYPES:
  A      - IPv4 address
  AAAA   - IPv6 address
  PTR    - Pointer (reverse lookup)
  CNAME  - Alias to another name

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

VERIFICATION
════════════
Create a file called 'dns_report.txt' with three lines:
  Line 1: IP address that 'server' resolves to
  Line 2: IP address that 'api' resolves to
  Line 3: The DNS server IP your container uses (from /etc/resolv.conf)

Run: ./verify

Success: You can query DNS servers, understand record types, and know why
external DNS servers cannot resolve internal station names.

